SIMPLE: extend
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Extend
<hw>Ex*tend"</hw> <pr>(⟦ecr⟧ks*t⟦ecr⟧nd")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Extended</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Extending</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>extendere</ets>, <ets>extentum</ets>, <ets>extensum</ets>;
<ets>ex</ets> out + <ets>tendere</ets> to stretch. See
<er>Trend</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To stretch out; to prolong in
space; to carry forward or continue in length; <as>as, to
<ex>extend</ex> a line in surveying; to <ex>extend</ex> a cord across
the street.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Few <qex>extend</qex> their thoughts toward universal
knowledge.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To enlarge, as a surface or volume; to expand; to
spread; to amplify; <as>as, to <ex>extend</ex> metal plates by hammering
or rolling them</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To enlarge; to widen; to carry out further; <as>as,
to <ex>extend</ex> the capacities, the sphere of usefulness, or
commerce; to <ex>extend</ex> power or influence</as>; to continue, as
time; to lengthen; to prolong; <as>as, to <ex>extend</ex> the time of
payment or a season of trial</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To hold out or reach forth, as the arm or
hand.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His helpless hand <qex>extend</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To bestow; to offer; to impart; to apply; <as>as, to
<ex>extend</ex> sympathy to the suffering</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To increase in quantity by weakening or adulterating
additions; <as>as, to <ex>extend</ex> liquors</as>.</def> <rj><au>G. P.
Burnham.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Eng. Law)</fld> <def>To value, as lands taken by a
writ of extent in satisfaction of a debt; to assign by writ of
extent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Extended letter</b></col> <fld>(Typog.)</fld>, <cd>a
letter, or style of type, having a broader face than is usual for a
letter or type of the same height.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <extendedtype>This is extended
type.</extendedtype></note></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To increase; enlarge; expand; widen; diffuse. See
<er>Increase</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Extendant</ent>⟦br⟧
